35519.object_definition_value: Succession disputes between the sons of Kodros in Athens result in some of them leading a large scale migration across the Aegean, perhaps stopping at Naxos on the way, and founding new cities in Anatolia. The leader of this migration is sometimes said to be Neileus, the founder claimed by Miletos, and sometimes said to be Androklos, the founder claimed by Ephesos. The composition of the accompanying large group is described variously by the different sources.

35519.object_definition_value:
The Lokrian hero Aias raped the Trojan Princess Cassandra in Athena's sanctuary during Troy's sack. The goddess, together with Poseidon, decided to avenge Aias, his fellow Lokrians and all the Achaeans while on their return home (nostoi).

In Odyssey, we read that Aias never made it back home (dysnostos). After a sea storm, Aias was driven to the Gyraean Rocks (between the islands of Tinos and Mykonos) before eventually drowning in the sea.

In Euripides's Troades, a vivid dialogue between the goddess Athena and the god Poseidon inform us about the tragic event of Cassandras's rape and represent the anger of the gods who decide to avenge the act while Aias and the Achaeans sail back home.

The myth is repeated with further details in two fragments of Kallimachos. Aias's corpse was washed ashore on the island of Delos, where Thetis found and buried him. The two fragments also inform us of the ritual of the Lokrian Maidens, which was initiated as part of the atonement for Aias's crime.

In Philostratos, we read a completely different version of Aias's behaviour during the Trojan War. Philostratos contradicts earlier myths that say Aias raped Kassandra, and instead, he argues that Aias did not rape her but dragged her from the temple to his tent as war booty. Agamemnon, jealous of her beauty, wanted to keep her as his own trophy. The story suspiciously resembles the known myth of conflict between Achilles and Agamemnon over Brisieis. The author continues on to say that Agamemnon framed Aias, spreading rumours that he raped her and that oracles dictated he had to be punished or all Greeks would have to pay the price. Aias ran away with a small boat during a stormy night and drowned in the sea close to the Gyrades rocks. Unlike other myths, Philostratos presents all the Greeks grieving for the death of a good soldier and vividly describes the funeral rites Aias received.

Strabo writes that Lokri Epizephyrioi was founded by the hero Evanthes and Lokrians who live close to the Corinthian Gulf (Western Lokrians). He contradicts an earlier account by Ephoros, who suggested Opountian foundation.
In 9.4.9, drawing on the homonymous towns of Alope in Lokri and Phthia, informs us that the Lokri Epizephyrioi in Italy was founded by the Western/Ozolian Lokrians, who were in turn founded by the Epiknemedian Lokrians.

Pseudo-Skymnos mentions both known versions of either Ozolian or Opountian foundation. He also mentions that Epizephyrian Lokrians were the first to write down laws (origins of social practice).

35519.object_definition_value:
The people of Amphissa claimed they were Aetolians to avoid the embarrassing name "Ozolians", although they were originally Lokrians.

Amphissa takes its name from the lover of Apollo, who was the daughter of Macar, son of Aeolus. According to Pausanias, there was also a burial monument dedicated to her in the city.

Harpokration cites Aristotle who supports that the founder of the city was Andraimon, while the city's name is due to the fact that it is surrounded by mountains.

Lokrian nostoi: Thoas, a Trojan hero from Amphissa, seems to be one of the few Lokrians who made it back home from war. It is said that he brought as war booty the bronze image of goddess Athena, which, at the time of Pausanias, was placed and worshipped in a temple on the Acropolis. Pausanias, however, is not convinced by this myth.

In Hyginus's Fabulae we have a list of the Argonauts. Amongst them are Menoitios from Opous, and Oileus from Naryx.

In Apollodorus' Argonautica, Menoitios, son of Aktor, was sent from Opous to join the Argonautic expedition. So too did the heroes Eurytion and Oileus.

In fragments of the Orphic Argonautica, we read again that the heroes Eurition (son of Aktor and king of Phthia), Menoitios and Oileos (both from Opous) joined the expedition.

Polybios presents two contradictory versions given by Aristotle and Timaeus regarding the foundation and origins of Lokri Epizephyrioi. He strongly supports the version of Aristotle and suggests that the Lokrians of Italy do so too. When he refers to the Lokris of Greece, he does not make specific mention of either East or West Lokris.

According to Polybios, the Lokrians of Italy claim matrilinear noble origins from the 100 Houses. Quoting Aristotle, he explains that the reason for migration was the romantic relationship between Lokrian women and their slaves. Lokri epizephyrioi was, thus, a colony of expelled women, slaves, and their illegitimate children. The settlers appropriated the Lokrian name and claimed shared origin, and even revied traditional affiliations such as long-standing friendships and alliances of the Lokrians. On the other hand, Timaeus account does not support the story of expelled slaves and instead argues for legitimate freemen who retained relations to their homeland.

35519.object_definition_value:
Strabo attributes the name Ozolian (coming from "ozein"=to smell) to the smell of a malodorous and clotted spring that flew down from the hill Taphiasus, at the top of which were the tombs of Nessus and other Centaurs.

Plutarch presents different versions of the name "Ozolians". The first one is again attributed to Nessus; The second to the serpent Python whose body rotted away in the country of the Lokrians; The third one, because these Lokrians wore fleeces and goatskins, lived close with herds of goats and hence smelled alike; The fourth version is the only one talking of a pleasant smell, coming from the odour of the many flowers flourishing in the country. 

Pausanias also presents different versions of the name "Ozolians".

The first story links the Lokrians to Oresthes, son of Deukalion, who planted a wooden stick in the Lokrian soil and knots (ozoi) branched. In other sources too, Lokrians claim affiliation and/or origins with Deukalion.
The other two stories attribute the name to a bad smell in the atmosphere of the whole country, coming either from the rotten corpse of Nessus or the exhalations of a river. Lastly, the name is attributed to the native ancestors of western Lokrians, who did not yet know how to properly weave garments and wore untanned animal skins and fleeces, which made their skin smell horrible.

In another passage of Pausanias (10.38.8), we read that the Lokrians of Amphissa claimed they were Aetolians as they were ashamed of the name "Ozolians".

Strabo explains that Daphnous, located at the exit of the Dipotamos corridor that linked the Kephissos valley to the Euboean Gulf, was once a Phokian city before being razed to the ground by the Lokrians. Phokian identity is claimed through a burial monument in the city which the story tells belongs to Schedios, the leader of the Phokians in the Trojan war.

Naupaktos derives its name from the practice of shipbuilding, once carried on there. Strabo informs us that the Herakleidai built their fleet there. He also quotes Ephoros who says that Lokrians were building ships there even before the time of the Herakleidai.
